# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: micro-frontends
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In software development, **front end** refers to the presentation layer that users interact with, while **back end** refers to the data management and processing behind the scenes.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In the client–server model, the client is usually considered the front end, handling most user-facing tasks, and the server is the back end, mainly managing data and logic.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In software architecture, there can be many layers between the hardware and end user.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] The *front end* is an abstraction, simplifying the underlying components by providing a user-friendly interface, while the *back end* handles data storage and business logic.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In telecommunication, the front end can be considered a device or service, while the back end is the infrastructure that supports the provision of services.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] A rule of thumb is that the front end, or client side, includes any components manipulated by the user.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] The back end, or server side, usually resides on the server, often far removed physically from the user.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] There are many different ways the terms 'front end' and 'back end' can be defined in the context of software.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] For example, in content management systems, the front end refers to views facing end users, and the back end refers to views facing administrative users.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] Similarly, within the field of speech synthesis, the front end refers to the part of the synthesis system that converts the input text into a symbolic phonetic representation, and the back end converts the symbolic phonetic representation into actual sounds.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In programming language compilers, the front end translates computer source code into an intermediate representation, and the back end produces executable code from the intermediate representation.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] The back end usually optimizes to produce code that runs faster.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] The front end/back end distinction can also separate a parser that deals with source code from a compiler that generates and optimizes executable code.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] Some designs, such as GCC, offer multiple front end options (parsing different source languages) and multiple back end options (generating code for different target processors).
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] Some graphical user interface (GUI) applications act as a thin front end for underlying command-line interface (CLI) programs, to save users from having to learn the CLI terminology and commands.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] Another way to understand the differences between the front end and back end is to consider the knowledge that each requires of a software developer.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] The example lists below focus on web development.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] The front end communicates with the back end through an API.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In the case of web and mobile front ends, the API is often based on HTTP requests/responses.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] An API can also reduce the front-end processing load by using different back-end services for different front-end interfaces, such as in the "Back end For Front end" (BFF) pattern.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In computer networking, *front end* can refer to hardware that connects devices to the network, provides security such as a DMZ, or converts data into a transportable format.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] *Back end* refers to hardware that handles and transports data within the network.
[src:micro-frontends/front-and-back-ends] In processor design, *front-end design* can refer to the initial description of a circuit's behavior in a hardware description language such as Verilog, while *back-end design* can refer to the process of mapping that behavior to physical transistors on a die.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] The **`HTMLIFrameElement`** interface provides special properties and methods (beyond those of the `HTMLElement` interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of inline frame elements.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that specifies the alignment of the frame with respect to the surrounding context.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that indicates the Permissions Policy specified for this `<iframe>`.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A boolean value indicating whether the inline frame is willing to be placed into full screen mode.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A boolean value indicating whether the Payment Request API may be invoked inside a cross-origin iframe.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A boolean property specifying that the selected topics for the current user should be sent with the request for the associated `<iframe>`'s source.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] This reflects the `browsingtopics` content attribute value.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Returns a `Document`, the active document in the inline frame's nested browsing context.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Returns a WindowProxy, the window proxy for the nested browsing context.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A boolean value indicating whether the `<iframe>` is credentialless, meaning that its content is loaded in a new, ephemeral context.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] This context does not have access to the parent context's shared storage and credentials.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] In return, the `Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy` (COEP) embedding rules can be lifted, so documents with COEP set can embed third-party documents that do not.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] See IFrame credentialless for a deeper explanation.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Specifies the Content Security Policy that an embedded document must agree to enforce upon itself.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Returns the `FeaturePolicy` interface which provides a simple API for introspecting the Permissions Policies applied to a specific document.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that indicates whether to create borders between frames.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that reflects the `height` HTML attribute, indicating the height of the frame.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string providing a hint to the browser that the iframe should be loaded immediately (`eager`) or on an as-needed basis (`lazy`).
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] This reflects the `loading` HTML attribute.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that contains the URI of a long description of the frame.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string being the height of the frame margin.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string being the width of the frame margin.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that reflects the `name` HTML attribute, containing a name by which to refer to the frame.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string representation of an options object representing a private state token operation; this object has the same structure as the `RequestInit` dictionary's `privateToken` property.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Mirrors the content of the associated `<iframe>` element's `privateToken` attribute.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that reflects the `referrerPolicy` HTML attribute indicating which referrer to use when fetching the linked resource.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Returns a `DOMTokenList` that reflects the `sandbox` HTML attribute, indicating extra restrictions on the behavior of the nested content.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that indicates whether the browser should provide scrollbars for the frame.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that reflects the `src` HTML attribute, containing the address of the content to be embedded.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Note that programmatically removing an `<iframe>`'s src attribute (e.g., via `Element.removeAttribute()`) causes `about:blank` to be loaded in the frame in Firefox (from version 65), Chromium-based browsers, and Safari/iOS.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A `TrustedHTML` or string that represents the HTML document loaded into the frame.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] A string that reflects the `width` HTML attribute, indicating the width of the frame.
[src:micro-frontends/htmliframeelement] Returns the embedded SVG as a `Document`.
[src:micro-frontends/micro-frontend] A **micro frontend** is an architectural pattern for web development, where independently developed frontends are composed into a greater whole.
[src:micro-frontends/micro-frontend] It is analogous to a microservices approach but for client-side single-page applications written in JavaScript.
[src:micro-frontends/micro-frontend] It is a solution to de-composition and routing for multiple front-end applications.
[src:micro-frontends/micro-frontend] Companies that use micro frontends are Canonical, IKEA, Scania AB, Spotify, etc.
[src:micro-frontends/micro-frontend] For Webpack this concept is referred to as module federation.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Modularity is a specific application of concerns to system components (separation by size).
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] In modular systems, each module encapsulates a single concern, and modules are designed, implemented, and understood in isolation before being composed into a larger system.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] While modularity is the most common and recognizable embodiment of SoC in code structure, the principle of Separation of concerns is broader.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] For example, separating requirements analysis from implementation in a project timeline, or separating functional from non-functional requirements in a specification, are valid forms of separation of concerns that do not necessarily require a modular design.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper *"On the Role of Scientific Thought"*, coined the term *separation of concerns* in relation to software qualities such as *correctness* and *efficiency*.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Carlo Ghezzi in his book "Fundamentals of software engineering" promotes Separation Of Concerns as the primary way to tackle the inherited complexity in software production.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Philippe Kruchten in his article "Architectural Blueprints—The “4+1” View Model of Software Architecture" used a model composed of five main views to address large architectures, essentially this is a view-based separation of concerns, where each view focus on a different aspect of the architecture.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Laplante, Phillip also mentioned that separation of concerns can be applied in software design, coding, time, and software qualities.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] The term *separation of concerns* was probably coined by Edsger W.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper "On the role of scientific thought".
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Fifteen years later, it was evident the term *separation of concerns* was becoming an accepted idea.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] SoC is crucial to the design of the Internet.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] In the Internet protocol suite, great efforts have been made to separate concerns into well-defined layers.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] This allows protocol designers to focus on the concerns in one layer, and ignore the other layers.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] The Application Layer protocol SMTP, for example, is concerned about all the details of conducting an email session over a reliable transport service (usually TCP), but not in the least concerned about how the transport service makes that service reliable.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Similarly, TCP is not concerned about the routing of data packets, which is handled at the Internet layer.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are complementary languages used in the development of web pages and websites.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] HTML is mainly used for organization of webpage content, CSS is used for definition of content presentation style, and JavaScript defines how the content interacts and behaves with the user.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Historically, this was not the case: prior to the introduction of CSS, HTML performed both duties of defining semantics and style.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Subject-oriented programming allows separate concerns to be addressed as separate software constructs, each on an equal footing with the others.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Each concern provides its own class-structure into which the objects in common are organized, and contributes state and methods to the composite result where they cut across one another.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Correspondence rules describe how the classes and methods in the various concerns are related to each other at points where they interact, allowing composite behavior for a method to be derived from several concerns.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Multi-dimensional SoC allows the analysis and composition of concerns to be manipulated as a multi-dimensional "matrix" in which each concern provides a dimension in which different points of choice are enumerated, with the cells of the matrix occupied by the appropriate software artifacts.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Aspect-oriented programming allows cross-cutting concerns to be addressed as primary concerns.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] For example, most programs require some form of security and logging.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Security and logging are often secondary concerns, whereas the primary concern is often on accomplishing business goals.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] However, when designing a program, its security must be built into the design from the beginning instead of being treated as a secondary concern.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] Applying security afterwards often results in an insufficient security model that leaves too many gaps for future attacks.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] This may be solved with aspect-oriented programming.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] For example, an aspect may be written to enforce that calls to a certain API are always logged, or that errors are always logged when an exception is thrown, regardless of whether the program's procedural code handles the exception or propagates it.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] In cognitive science and artificial intelligence, it is common to refer to David Marr's levels of analysis.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] At any given time, a researcher may be focusing on what some aspect of intelligence needs to compute, what algorithm it employs, or how that algorithm is implemented in hardware.
[src:micro-frontends/separation-of-concerns] This separation of concerns is similar to the interface/implementation distinction in software and hardware engineering.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Web Components is a suite of different technologies allowing you to create reusable custom elements — with their functionality encapsulated away from the rest of your code — and utilize them in your web apps.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] As developers, we all know that reusing code as much as possible is a good idea.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] This has traditionally not been so easy for custom markup structures — think of the complex HTML (and associated style and script) you've sometimes had to write to render custom UI controls, and how using them multiple times can turn your page into a mess if you are not careful.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Web Components aims to solve such problems — it consists of three main technologies, which can be used together to create versatile custom elements with encapsulated functionality that can be reused wherever you like without fear of code collisions.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A set of JavaScript APIs that allow you to define custom elements and their behavior, which can then be used as desired in your user interface.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A set of JavaScript APIs for attaching an encapsulated "shadow" DOM tree to an element — which is rendered separately from the main document DOM — and controlling associated functionality.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] In this way, you can keep an element's features private, so they can be scripted and styled without the fear of collision with other parts of the document.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The `<template>` and `<slot>` elements enable you to write markup templates that are not displayed in the rendered page.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] These can then be reused multiple times as the basis of a custom element's structure.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Register your new custom element using the `CustomElementRegistry.define()` method, passing it the element name to be defined, the class or function in which its functionality is specified, and optionally, what element it inherits from.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] You can register on the global registry via `Window.customElements`, or create a scoped registry using the `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor to avoid name conflicts between components.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] If required, attach a shadow DOM to the custom element using `Element.attachShadow()` method.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Add child elements, event listeners, etc., to the shadow DOM using regular DOM methods.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] If required, define an HTML template using `<template>` and `<slot>`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Again use regular DOM methods to clone the template and attach it to your shadow DOM.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Use your custom element wherever you like on your page, just like you would any regular HTML element.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A guide showing how to use the features of custom elements to create simple web components, as well as looking into lifecycle callbacks and some other more advanced features.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A guide that looks at shadow DOM fundamentals, showing how to attach a shadow DOM to an element, add to the shadow DOM tree, style it, and more.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A guide showing how to define a reusable HTML structure using `<template>` and `<slot>` elements, and then use that structure inside your web components.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Contains functionality related to custom elements, most notably the `CustomElementRegistry.define()` method used to register new custom elements so they can then be used in your document.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor can be used to create scoped registries, and the `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()` method associates a scoped registry with a DOM subtree.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Returns a reference to the global `CustomElementRegistry` object.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry` associated with the document.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry` associated with the element.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Invoked when the custom element is first connected to the document's DOM.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Invoked when the custom element is disconnected from the document's DOM.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Invoked when the custom element is moved to a new document.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Invoked when one of the custom element's attributes is added, removed, or changed.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Allows you to specify that a standard HTML element should behave like a registered customized built-in element.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Allows you to create an instance of a standard HTML element that behaves like a given registered customized built-in element.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Matches any element that is defined, including built in elements and custom elements defined with `CustomElementRegistry.define()`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Selects the shadow host of the shadow DOM containing the CSS it is used inside.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Selects the shadow host of the shadow DOM containing the CSS it is used inside (so you can select a custom element from inside its shadow DOM) — but only if the selector given as the function's parameter matches the shadow host.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Selects the shadow host of the shadow DOM containing the CSS it is used inside (so you can select a custom element from inside its shadow DOM) — but only if the selector given as the function's parameter matches the shadow host's ancestor(s) in the place it sits inside the DOM hierarchy.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Matches custom elements that are in a specified custom state.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] More precisely, it matches anonymous custom elements where the specified state is present in the element's `CustomStateSet`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Represents any element within a shadow tree that has a matching `part` attribute.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Represents the root node of a shadow DOM subtree.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The `CustomElementRegistry` associated with the shadow root.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Can be set via the `customElementRegistry` option of `Element.attachShadow()`, or later using `CustomElementRegistry.initialize()`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Returns `true` if the event will propagate across the shadow DOM boundary into the standard DOM, otherwise `false`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Returns the event's path (objects on which listeners will be invoked).
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] This does not include nodes in shadow trees if the shadow root was created with `ShadowRoot.mode` closed.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Contains an HTML fragment that is not rendered when a containing document is initially loaded, but can be displayed at runtime using JavaScript, mainly used as the basis of custom element structures.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The associated DOM interface is `HTMLTemplateElement`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A placeholder inside a web component that you can fill with your own markup, which lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] The associated DOM interface is `HTMLSlotElement`.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Assigns a slot in a shadow DOM shadow tree to an element.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A read-only attribute which returns a reference to the `<slot>` in which this element is inserted.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] A read-only attribute which returns a reference to the `<slot>` in which this text node is inserted.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Returns the name of the shadow DOM slot attached to the element.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Matches any content that is inserted into a slot.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] Fired on an `HTMLSlotElement` instance (`<slot>` element) when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:micro-frontends/web-components] We are building up a number of examples in our web-components-examples GitHub repo.
